{
  "answer": "**In the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* (Chapter 1, verses 1.4–1.5), Yājñavalkya is named as one of the sages who promulgated the Dharmaśāstras.**[^1][^2]\n\nVerse 1.4 lists: \"Manu, Atri, Viṣṇu, Hārīta, **Yājñavalkya**, Uśanas, Aṅgiras, Yama, Āpastamba, Saṃvarta, Kātyāyana, and Bṛhaspati.\" Verse 1.5 continues the list—\"Parāśara, Vyāsa, Śaṅkha, Likhita, Dakṣa, and Gautama, Śātātapa, and Vasiṣṭha\"—and explicitly states that (all these sages) \"are the promulgators of the Dharmaśāstras.\"[^1][^2]\n\nThis opening passage frames the text by honoring Yājñavalkya (the work's traditional author) while crediting him alongside other foundational lawgivers in the Smṛti tradition.\n\n[^1]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-0f4ad0](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-0f4ad0).\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-95ef53](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-95ef53).",
